
[1]startle

   STARTLE, v.i. [dim. of start.] To shrink; to move suddenly or be
   excited on feeling a sudden alarm.

   Why shrinks the soul back on herself, and startles at destruction?

                                STARTLE, v.t.

   1. To impress with fear; to excite by sudden alarm, surprise or
   apprehension; to shock; to alarm; to fright. We were startled at the
   cry of distress. Any great and unexpected event is apt to startle us.

   The supposition that angles assume bodies, need not startle us.

   2. To deter; to cause to deviate. [Little used.]

   STARTLE, n. A sudden motion or shock occasioned by an unexpected alarm,
      surprise or apprehension of danger; sudden impression of terror.

   After having recovered from my first startle, I was well pleased with
   the accident.
